<title>Introduction to MATE</title>

<comment>
  <cite date="2014-12-04">MotoHosss</cite>
  <p>draft update - improvements welcome.</p>
</comment>

<p>MATE provides an intuitive and attractive desktop to Linux users using
traditional metaphors. MATE features a complete multi-tasking user interface
to help you get things done and design your work-flow. You will see an empty
desktop and two panels when you login for the first time. </p>

<media type="image" src="figures/mate-default-top-panel.png"
       width="500" height="40">
  <p>MATE shell top bar</p>
</media>

<p>The top panel provides access to any of a number of panel applets, your
calendar and weather, and system properties like sound, networking, and
power. The traditional menu system is available in the top panel with
"Applications" and "Places" with all preferences in their usual location under the
"System" menu. One can set availability, change your profile or any number of
tweaks. The user may log out, switch users or turn off the computer.</p>

<p>The lower panel provides access to any of a number of panel applets
as well. By default it has the WorkSpace Switcher, Show Desktop and the
Window List applets. There are many applets to choose from. Either the
top or lower panel can be customized by simply right clicking a vacant
portion of either panel.</p>

<media type="image" src="figures/mate-default-lower-panel.png"
       width="500" height="40">
  <p>MATE shell top bar</p>
</media>

