<section id="activities">
<title>Panel overview</title>

<media type="image" src="figures/mate-add-to-panel-rtclick.png"
       width="128" height="75" style="floatright">
  <p>Add to Panel 'right-click'</p>
</media>

<p>To access your running windows and applications, click on the beveled
bar in the lower panel. If you want to start a different or new
application they can be found under the <em>Applications</em> menu on
the top panel. Any number of applications can be added to either panel
by means of a launcher that can be added by the <em>Add to Panel</em>
applet which can be accesed by a right-click on either panel.</p>

<media type="image" src="figures/mate-panel-windowlist.png"
       width="170" height="150" style="floatleft">
      <p>Window List</p>
</media>

<p>On the left of the lower panel you will find the <em>Window List</em>.
The Window List applet will allow preferences settings so you can
conviently show your current open application either on this workspace
or on all workspaces. Click any application just to the right of the and
that application will open.</p>

<p>If you right-click on any of those applications in the list you can
make one of several choices of what to do with that window. You can
Minimize, Maximize or even move it to another workspace... all just by a
simple click. You can also drag the invidual list members onto any
workspace thumbnail on the right.</p>

<media type="image" src="figures/mate-panel-workspaceswitcher.png"
       width="430" height="40" style="floatleft">
      <p>WorkSpace Switcher</p>
</media>

<p>On the lower panel right side is where the Workspace Switcher applet
lives by default. It will show four workspaces by default. When you move
the mouse over the applet it will give you a hint as to which workspace
it is over by a tool-tip. These names can be easily customized with a
right-click then selecting "Properties" with your mouse over the applet
area. The applet shows you an informal or relative view of what is on
each workspace.</p>

<p>Click <gui>Applications</gui> to enter the MATE main menu. This menu
shows you all the available applications installed on your computer.
Click any application to run it, or drag an the item to either panel or
the desktop to have a custom place for you most used programs.</p>

